<!doctype html>
<html lang="en">
  <head>
    <BaseHead
      title="Git & GitHub — Learning Notes"
      description="My learning notes while understanding Git and GitHub."
    />
  </head>

  <body>
    <Header />

    <main>
        <article>
            <h1>Git & GitHub</h1>

            <p class="status comfortable">
                Status: Comfortable
            </p>

            <p class="note-disclaimer">
                These are my personal learning notes. They reflect how I currently
                understand Git and GitHub and may evolve as I use them more.
            </p>

            <!-- WHY -->
            <section>
                <h2>Why I learned Git</h2>
                <p>
                I reached a point where manual versioning (<code>final.js</code>,
                <code>final_v2.js</code>) became unmanageable.
                Git wasn’t optional anymore — it was the only sane way to track changes,
                undo mistakes, and collaborate.
                </p>
            </section>

            <!-- CORE CONCEPT -->
            <section>
                <h2>The core idea that matters</h2>
                <p>
                Git is a <strong>local version control system</strong>.
                GitHub is a <strong>remote hosting service</strong>.
                </p>
                <ul>
                <li>Git tracks changes and history on my machine</li>
                <li>GitHub stores and shares that history online</li>
                <li>You can use Git without GitHub, but not the other way around</li>
                </ul>
            </section>

            <!-- MENTAL MODEL -->
            <section>
                <h2>The mental model that clicked</h2>
                <ul>
                <li><strong>Working Directory</strong> → where I edit files</li>
                <li><strong>Staging Area</strong> → what I choose to save</li>
                <li><strong>Repository</strong> → permanent history</li>
                </ul>
                <p>
                Understanding this made commands like <code>add</code> and
                <code>commit</code> feel logical instead of magical.
                </p>
            </section>

            <!-- DAILY WORKFLOW -->
            <section>
                <h2>The workflow I actually use</h2>
                <pre><code>git status
            git add .
            git commit -m "Clear, specific message"
            git push</code></pre>

                <ul>
                <li><code>git status</code> is my most-used command</li>
                <li>I commit small, logical changes</li>
                <li>I push frequently to avoid losing work</li>
                </ul>
            </section>

            <!-- BRANCHING -->
            <section>
                <h2>Branching (how I think about it)</h2>
                <p>
                Branches are parallel timelines.
                I use them to experiment without risking the main codebase.
                </p>
                <pre><code>git checkout -b feature-name
            git checkout main
            git merge feature-name</code></pre>
                <p>
                I keep branches short-lived and delete them after merging.
                </p>
            </section>

            <!-- GITHUB -->
            <section>
                <h2>How GitHub fits in</h2>
                <ul>
                <li>Acts as a backup for my repositories</li>
                <li>Makes collaboration possible</li>
                <li>Provides visibility into my work history</li>
                </ul>
                <p>
                For now, I mainly use GitHub as a remote and for sharing projects.
                </p>
            </section>

            <!-- GOOD PRACTICES -->
            <section>
                <h2>Practices I try to follow</h2>
                <ul>
                <li>Meaningful commit messages</li>
                <li>Using <code>.gitignore</code> correctly</li>
                <li>Not committing secrets or generated files</li>
                <li>Keeping commit history readable</li>
                </ul>
            </section>

            <!-- MISTAKES -->
            <section>
                <h2>Mistakes I made while learning</h2>
                <ul>
                <li>Committing too much in one commit</li>
                <li>Pushing without checking <code>git status</code></li>
                <li>Fear of branches initially</li>
                <li>Not understanding merge conflicts early</li>
                </ul>
            </section>

            <!-- WHAT I DON'T KNOW YET -->
            <section>
                <h2>What I haven’t gone deep into yet</h2>
                <ul>
                <li>Rebasing vs merging in complex scenarios</li>
                <li>Advanced conflict resolution</li>
                <li>Git hooks and automation</li>
                <li>Large-team workflows</li>
                </ul>
            </section>

            <!-- NEXT -->
            <section>
                <h2>How I’ll deepen this later</h2>
                <ul>
                <li>Use Git daily in real projects</li>
                <li>Handle real merge conflicts</li>
                <li>Review old commits critically</li>
                </ul>
            </section>

            <!-- NAV -->
            <nav class="note-nav">
                <a href="/learning-paths/notes/javascript">← JavaScript</a>
                <span class="disabled"> →</span>
            </nav>
        </article>

    </main>

    <Footer />
  </body>
</html>
